It was so special to put this package together for @camrynmary in honor of Suicide Prevention Month, and watching her unbox it is even more special 🥺 Thank you Camryn for being a proud suicide prevention advocate. We are so lucky to have you in this community because we know that together we can help stop suicide. 

Hope every single reminder we included supports you when you need it. 💙

This month, 100% of the profits from our ‘Together We Can Help Stop Suicide’ collection goes to @afspnational ✨🤍

node.text:
🙏 Healing is never linear. Healing is a journey, one that has unexpected twists and turns, but — just speaking from our experience — when you are present for the process, it can feel easier to learn to be your own ally. 

🌱 The journey doesn't feel so overwhelming when you are able to become present with just this step. And then the next. 

🌻 By slowing everything down, it becomes easier to check-in with yourself. To adjust your approach. To switch out your tools. To know when you need to rest, and when you are ready to take on mountains. 🏔

( 🎨 by @worrywellbeing )

node.text:
🌻 How Are You, Really? This question represents one of many ways to further a conversation and invite vulnerability in an effort to strengthen connections, combat isolation and help stop suicide. 

Thank you @curly_therapist for the work you do to support others in conversations about mental health and suicide, we are so grateful to have you in our community. 💕

💙 This month, our campaign is centered around encouraging all communities to become more comfortable talking about suicide and checking in on loved ones and their mental health. That is why we included this gorgeous reminder that says, "How Are You, Really?"

Instead of leaving it to the person in crisis to be the one asking for help, we are empowering our community toward checking in on their loved ones and those in their own community. 🦋

Together we can help #stopsuicide

node.text:
🧠 Monday Mental Health Check-In!! 

👇How have you been feeling? If you had to pick a weather emoji to describe your mind today, which would you pick? 
Feel free to also explain why you picked that emoji!!
☀️🌤⛅️🌥☁️🌦🌧⛈🌩🌨❄️🌫🌪⚡️ 

Responding to someone else in the comments with some love and kindness is encouraged #community 💕✨😊🙏 

🌪Some days our emotions can feel like there is a storm happening inside of our mind (with a forecast of tears and anxiety) and maybe other days you wake up and your mind is just feeling foggy but later on the fog clears up and you’re feeling sunny. Either way, your emotions can fluctuate and change as the day goes on. 

♥️ If you need support in a challenging time:

What you are experiencing can really impact your mental health and ability to focus. We wanted to include some resources of where you can reach out for support if it ever feels quite challenging. 🙏

All US residents can Text HOME to 741741 Crisis Text Line is available 24/7 to connect you with a trained crisis counselor ready to help you through any situation you’re finding challenging. This can range from school stress to coronavirus anxiety, depression to suicidal thoughts, and everything in between. A safe and confidential platform, Crisis Text Line can help you through your most difficult moments.

To find more resources (including inside or outside of the USA) check out our Mental Health Resources on our website. ♥️🙏 It’s okay to ask for help, you are not alone!! 

Sending you all so much love ♥️🌈

node.text:
Together we can help stop suicide. 💙 

It has been the greatest honor to collaborate with @afspnational @chickofalltrade and @shopsundae for this Suicide Prevention Campaign. 

This month is so important to our community. In 2019, the most recent year of data from the National Institute of Mental Health, suicide was the second leading cause of death among individuals between the ages of 10 and 34 😞

The world can feel like a really dark  place at times and it can feel scary to ask for help. We know that we have so much work to do in order to continue making an impact but we are determined 🌎

Together we can accomplish so much more, especially when we share in a common vision as a community. 

Our mission at Self-Care Is For Everyone is to spread reminders that promote mental health and help to prevent suicide. 🦋

🙏 We are so grateful to our community for wearing these messages and reminders for the world to see every single day. These are conversation starters and powerful reminders that so many of us need more of throughout our days. Without the support of each of you, this work would not be possible. 

Together we will end the stigma and help stop suicide 💓

Save this conversation guide in case you ever need support in knowing how to respond. 💙

How to check in with a friend you are worried about

node.text:
🦋 In honor of Suicide Prevention Week, we will be sharing conversation guides that we have co-created with @afspnational here on Instagram all week long. 💙

💞 Our hope is to support our community in having these difficult conversations. 

🧠 While it has become increasingly more common to talk about mental health, particularly this past year, the topic of suicide – when it comes up – is still scary for many people to think about, let alone say the word: Suicide.

🌧 Some may be afraid that by asking someone if they’re having thoughts of suicide, it will put the idea in their head, or perhaps push them to take their own life. (Which research shows is not true.) 

Others are worried that they won’t know what to do, or how to help if the person tells them, “Yes – I am thinking about suicide.”

🌈 We see this as an opportunity to deepen the conversation. We all have mental health. It’s time we take the next step, checking in on one another's mental health, and if we need it, find help together.

🧡 Together we can help #stopsuicide

♥️ If you need support in a challenging time:

What you are experiencing can really impact your mental health and ability to focus. We wanted to include some resources of where you can reach out for support if it ever feels quite challenging. 🙏

All US residents can Text HOME to 741741 Crisis Text Line is available 24/7 to connect you with a trained crisis counselor ready to help you through any situation you’re finding challenging. This can range from school stress to coronavirus anxiety, depression to suicidal thoughts, and everything in between. A safe and confidential platform, Crisis Text Line can help you through your most difficult moments.

To find more resources (including inside or outside of the USA) check out our Mental Health Resources on our website. ♥️🙏 It’s okay to ask for help, you are not alone!!

Sending you all so much love ♥️🌈
